<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910816-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>910816-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Tele-Communications Inc.:   Cable Operator's Net Loss   Narrowed in 2nd Quarter</HL><DATE>08/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   TCOMA TCOMB</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>COLORADO (CO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest cablesystems operator, reported a narrower loss on increasedrevenue for the second quarter. The company, based in Denver,posted a net loss of $25 million, or seven cents a share, onrevenue of $922 million, compared with a net loss of $44million, or 12 cents a share, on revenues of $890 million in1990.   Cash flow, or operating income before interest,depreciation and amortization, increased by nearly 10% to$375 million for the second quarter, compared with $341million in 1990. Cable operators use cash flow as the primaryindicator of performance.</LP><TEXT>   For the six-month period, Tele-Communications posted a netloss of $50 million, or 14 cents a share, on revenue of $1.85billion, compared with a net loss of $111 million, or 31cents a share, on revenue of $1.75 billion in 1990.</TEXT></DOC>